<paper>
Paper Title: Can Generative AI improve social science?
Paper Abstract: Generative AI that can produce realistic text, images, and other human-like outputs is currently transforming many different industries. Yet it is not yet known how such tools might influence social science research. I argue Generative AI has the potential to improve survey research, online experiments, automated content analyses, agent-based models, and other techniques commonly used to study human behavior. In the second section of this article, I discuss the many limitations of Generative AI. I examine how bias in the data used to train these tools can negatively impact social science researchâ€”as well as a range of other challenges related to ethics, replication, environmental impact, and the proliferation of low-quality research. I conclude by arguing that social scientists can address many of these limitations by creating open-source infrastructure for research on human behavior. Such infrastructure is not only necessary to ensure broad access to high-quality research tools, I argue, but also because the progress of AI will require deeper understanding of the social forces that guide human behavior.
</paper>

<paper_classification>
"contribution" = proposes something new (method, technique, dataset, framework, benchmark, etc.)
"survey" = literature review, overview, meta-analysis, position papers (only references existing work)
</paper_classification>

<entity_types>
task      - Problem being solved (image classification, theorem proving, protein folding)
method    - Technique, algorithm, procedure (gradient descent, CRISPR, induction)
data      - Datasets, databases, benchmarks (ImageNet, MNIST, arXiv corpus)
artifact  - Pre-built: trained models, proof libraries (GPT-4, Mathlib, Cas9)
tool      - Software, instruments, platforms (PyTorch, Lean prover, microscope)
concept   - Abstract ideas, theories, frameworks (attention, category theory)
other     - Entities that don't fit above categories
</entity_types>

<relations>
uses     - Anything EXISTING that the paper uses (methods, datasets, tools, concepts, tasks)
proposes - Anything NEW/NOVEL that the paper creates or introduces

VALIDATION REQUIREMENTS:
- ALL papers MUST have at least 1 "uses" (papers always build on existing work)
- CONTRIBUTION papers MUST have at least 1 "proposes" (they must create something new)
</relations>

<output_json>
{
  "paper_type": "contribution" or "survey",
  "triples": [
    {
      "name": "Wikipedia Article Title",
      "relation": "uses|proposes",
      "entity_type": "task|method|data|artifact|tool|concept|other",
      "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/...",
      "relevance": "Why this matters (1 sentence)"
    }
  ]
}
</output_json>

<YOUR_TODO_LIST>
FIRST, add ALL of these to your todo list with "TodoWrite" tool:

CRITICAL: Todo content must be copied exactly as is written here, with NO CHANGES. These todos are intentionally detailed so that another LLM could read each one without any external context and understand exactly what it has to do.

1. Read ./triples_output.json. Classify paper as "contribution" or "survey". Edit triples_output.json to set paper_type field.

2. List ALL triples EXPLICITLY mentioned in title/abstract. For each, determine entity_type and relation.

3. For each triple: Use WebSearch tool with allowed_domains=["en.wikipedia.org"] to search "[entity name]" to find the correct Wikipedia article. IMPORTANT: Always include allowed_domains parameter to restrict to English Wikipedia.

4. Edit triples_output.json to add all triples. For each triple:
   - name: Use the Wikipedia article title (e.g., "Gradient descent" not "gradient descent algorithm")
   - relation: how paper relates to entity (uses or proposes)
   - entity_type: one of task, method, data, artifact, tool, concept, other
   - wikipedia_url: The Wikipedia URL from search results (must start with https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/)
   - relevance: 1 sentence explaining why it matters

5. Run validation: python validate_triple_json.py

6. If validation errors: Fix the errors (use WebSearch with allowed_domains=["en.wikipedia.org"] again if needed for incorrect URLs), edit triples_output.json, and rerun validation. MUST REPEAT until validation passes.

<CRITICAL_WEBSEARCH_INSTRUCTIONS>
When using WebSearch, you MUST use the allowed_domains parameter:
WebSearch(query="[your query]", allowed_domains=["en.wikipedia.org"])

This ensures only English Wikipedia results are returned. Do NOT search without allowed_domains.
</CRITICAL_WEBSEARCH_INSTRUCTIONS>
</YOUR_TODO_LIST>

Begin now.

## Content Analysis

Content analysis is the study of documents and communication artifacts, including texts, photos, speeches, or essays.(no content)Social scientists use content analysis to examine patterns in communication in a replicable and systematic manner.

### Key Characteristics

Content analysis involves systematic reading or observation of texts or artifacts which are assigned labels (called codes) to indicate meaningful pieces of content. By systematically labeling content in a set of texts, researchers can analyze patterns quantitatively using statistical methods, or use qualitative methods to analyze meanings within texts.

### Approaches

There are two main approaches to content analysis:

- **Quantitative content analysis**: This highlights frequency counts and statistical analysis of coded frequencies, and begins with a framed hypothesis with coding decided on before analysis begins.

- **Qualitative content analysis**: This focuses more on intentionality and its implications.

### Applications and Tools

Computers are increasingly used in content analysis to automate the labeling of documents. Simple computational techniques can provide descriptive data such as word frequencies and document lengths.(no content)One of the key advantages of using content analysis is its non-invasive nature, in contrast to simulating social experiences or collecting survey answers.

## Web-Based Experiments

A web-based experiment or Internet-based experiment is an experiment that is conducted over the Internet.(no content)The Internet is either "a medium through which to target larger and more diverse samples with reduced administrative and financial costs" or serves as a field for social science research.

### Key Benefits

Web-based experiments are significantly less expensive and allow researchers to reach more diverse samples and rare sub-populations, which can translate into greater external validity and generalizability for studies. Additionally, because participants remain in their homes or offices while participating in the experiment, scholars have argued that such experiments have greater ecological validity.

### Challenges

Web-based experiments may have weaker experimental controls compared to laboratory-based experiments, and may face greater difficulties coming up with procedures that ensure reliability and internal validity.(no content)Some potential difficulties include difficulty verifying participant identity, instructions being read carelessly, shorter decision times triggering emotional rather than rational reasoning, significant distractions, selective dropout, and variance due to network and computer differences.

### Applications

A wide range of psychology experiments are conducted on the web, with The Web Experiment List providing a way to recruit participants and archiving over 700 past experiments.(no content)Web experiments have been used to validate results from laboratory and field research and to conduct new experiments that are only feasible if done online.

## What is an Agent-Based Model?

An agent-based model (ABM) is a computational model for simulating the actions and interactions of autonomous agents (both individual or collective entities such as organizations or groups) in order to understand the behavior of a system and what governs its outcomes.

## How They Work

Agent-based models are a kind of microscale model that simulate the simultaneous operations and interactions of multiple agents in an attempt to re-create and predict the appearance of complex phenomena.(no content)The process is one of emergence, which some express as "the whole is greater than the sum of its parts" - in other words, higher-level system properties emerge from the interactions of lower-level subsystems.(no content)Individual agents are typically characterized as boundedly rational, presumed to be acting in what they perceive as their own interests, such as reproduction, economic benefit, or social status, using heuristics or simple decision-making rules.

## Applications and Development

ABMs are typically implemented as computer simulations, either as custom software, or via ABM toolkits, and this software can be then used to test how changes in individual behaviors will affect the system's emerging overall behavior.

ABMs have diverse applications across fields, including transportation, market failures, cooperation and escalation and spreading of conflicts, as well as biology and economics.
